{"title_page": "Eric Franklin Rosser", "text_new": "'''Eric Franklin Rosser''' (born January 17, 1952)<ref>https://nypost.com/2001/08/26/perverts-bizarre-life-on-run/</ref> also known as '''Doc Rosser''', is a former keyboardist for [[John Mellencamp]]. He joined Mellencamp's band in 1979 and toured with Mellencamp for over two years. He recorded with the band only on Mellencamp's 1980 album ''[[Nothin' Matters and What If It Did]]'' and on ''[[American Fool]]'' in 1982, before leaving the band. Rosser is infamous for being on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]'s \"Ten Most Wanted Fugitives\" list for his alleged involvement in the production and distribution of child pornography in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1435444/12272000/mellencamp_john.jhtml |title=Ex-Mellencamp Keyboardist One Of FBI's Ten Most Wanted |accessdate=2012-04-12 |publisher=Viacom International Inc |date=27 December 2000 |author=Joe D'Angelo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050824040004/http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1435444/12272000/mellencamp_john.jhtml |archivedate=2005-08-24}}</ref> He had been living in [[Bangkok]] at the time and had been on the run due to a failure to appear. He was arrested in August 2001 for carrying false information, and was [[extradited]] back to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2001/10/22/rosser_2/ |title=The man with the naked piano |accessdate=2012-04-12 |date=22 October 2001 |author=Douglas Wissing |publisher=Salon Media Group, Inc}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRosser was born in Syracuse, New York to Donna, a watercolor artist, and Richard Rosser, a retired Air Force Colonel and retired DePauw University president. He attended [[Air Academy High School]] in [[Colorado]], and graduated from [[London Central Elementary High School|London Central High School]], a USAF-run school located in [[Bushy Park|Bushy, UK]] in 1970. Eric Rosser got his bachelor's degree in music from Oberlin in 1974, and a master's degree from Indiana University in 1979. Rosser lived in Bloomington, Indiana until the early 1990s, when he moved to Thailand and began giving piano lessons to students who would become among his victims. Between August 1995 and August 1997, Rosser frequently visited Bloomington from Thailand, and during these visits Rosser victimized three American girls, aged 9 to 11 years old.<ref name=\":1\">https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/389885310/ ''Chicago Tribune'', Monday February 26, 2001, page 14</ref>\n\n==Conviction==\nIn April 2000, Rosser was indicted by a federal grand jury in Indianapolis and fled to Thailand.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was sentenced to over 16 years after an investigation revealed he had recorded himself sexually assaulting a young girl, and then traded it to an Indiana man for different pornographic material.<ref name=\":0\" />\nAs of 2012, Rosser was incarcerated at [[Federal Correctional Complex, Butner|FCI Butner Low]].<ref>\"[http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Eric&Middle=Franklin&LastName=Rosser&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 Eric Franklin Rosser].\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/67kL6o5sH?url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction%3DNameSearch%26needingMoreList%3Dfalse%26FirstName%3DEric%26Middle%3DFranklin%26LastName%3DRosser%26Race%3DU%26Sex%3DU%26Age%3D%26x%3D0%26y%3D0 Archive]). [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]. Retrieved on May 18, 2012.</ref> He was released on January 13, 2017.\n\n==Release and new charges==\nIn July 2017, Rosser was caught watching child pornography as he fled [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] on a bus, with $10,000 strapped to each of his legs, a bag with $50,000, and $1000 worth of cannabis. He pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]]. He admitted that he was fleeing federal probation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRosser pleaded guilty to accessing the internet with intent to view child pornography after signing a plea agreement with prosecutors in October 2018.\n\nAccording to court documents filed by federal prosecutors, Rosser was riding on a bus from [[Butte, Montana|Butte]] to [[Billings, Montana|Billings]] in July 2017 when another man noticed child pornography on his screen. When the man approached Rosser about it, he reportedly said, \"Leave me alone. I know I have a problem\", according to court documents.\n\nThe fellow passenger called Billings police to the bus station, and when they arrived, Rosser admitted to looking at the images of young girls engaging in sexually explicit conduct. Police also found he had $10,000 in cash strapped to each leg, along with $50,000 in cash in his luggage and approximately $1,000 worth of marijuana, which he told police he purchased for personal use, according to court records.\n\nRosser additionally admitted to violating his probation conditions and fleeing federal supervision in Washington state, court documents say. He said he had emptied his bank account and fled to avoid going back to prison. \n\nOn Tuesday, Rosser told U.S. Magistrate Judge Jeremiah Lynch he did not dispute any of the information brought forth by federal prosecutors. Lynch said he would be sentenced to a minimum of 10 years and may be on supervised release for the rest of his life following the prison term. \n\nHis sentencing was set for January 17, 2019.<ref> https://missoulian.com/news/crime/man-found-watching-child-porn-on-montana-bus-with-k/article_317217dd-329f-5512-8405-0fe28acada1f.html </ref>\nOn February 21, 2020, Rosser was sentenced to ten years in prison, and to permanent supervision if he is ever released.<ref name=\":0\">https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/crime-and-courts/former-mellencamp-pianist-gets-prison-again-this-time-for-watching/article_c137b13c-4daa-5833-91f4-79ed78a62b01.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Perry, J.J. \"[http://www.heraldtimesonline.com/stories/1999/05/21/scene.990521_D3_JJP14157.sto Eric Rosser].\" ''[[Herald-Times]]''. May 21, 1999.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosser, Eric Franklin}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Thailand]]\n[[Category:People extradited to the United States]]\n[[Category:American pornographers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Eric Franklin Rosser''' (born January 17, 1952)<ref>https://nypost.com/2001/08/26/perverts-bizarre-life-on-run/</ref> also known as '''Doc Rosser''', is a former keyboardist for [[John Mellencamp]]. He joined Mellencamp's band in 1979 and toured with Mellencamp for over two years. He recorded with the band only on Mellencamp's 1980 album ''[[Nothin' Matters and What If It Did]]'' and on ''[[American Fool]]'' in 1982, before leaving the band. Rosser is infamous for being on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]'s \"Ten Most Wanted Fugitives\" list for his alleged involvement in the production and distribution of child pornography in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1435444/12272000/mellencamp_john.jhtml |title=Ex-Mellencamp Keyboardist One Of FBI's Ten Most Wanted |accessdate=2012-04-12 |publisher=Viacom International Inc |date=27 December 2000 |author=Joe D'Angelo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050824040004/http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1435444/12272000/mellencamp_john.jhtml |archivedate=2005-08-24}}</ref> He had been living in [[Bangkok]] at the time and had been on the run due to a failure to appear. He was arrested in August 2001 for carrying false information, and was [[extradited]] back to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2001/10/22/rosser_2/ |title=The man with the naked piano |accessdate=2012-04-12 |date=22 October 2001 |author=Douglas Wissing |publisher=Salon Media Group, Inc}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRosser was born in Syracuse, New York to Donna, a watercolor artist, and Richard Rosser, a retired Air Force Colonel and retired DePauw University president. He attended [[Air Academy High School]] in [[Colorado]], and graduated from [[London Central Elementary High School|London Central High School]], a USAF-run school located in [[Bushy Park|Bushy, UK]] in 1970. Eric Rosser got his bachelors degree in music from Oberlin in 1974, and a masters degree from Indiana University in 1979. Rosser lived in Bloomington, Indiana until the early 1990s, when he moved to Thailand and began giving piano lessons to students who would become among his victims. Between August 1995 and August 1997, Rosser frequently visited Bloomington from Thailand, and during these visits Rosser victimized three American girls, aged 9 to 11 years old.<ref name=\":1\">https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/389885310/ ''Chicago Tribune'', Monday February 26, 2001, page 14</ref>\n\n==Conviction==\nIn April 2000, Rosser was indicted by a federal grand jury in Indianapolis and fled to Thailand.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was sentenced to over 16 years after an investigation revealed he had recorded himself sexually assaulting a young girl, and then traded it to an Indiana man for different pornographic material.<ref name=\":0\" />\nAs of 2012, Rosser was incarcerated at [[Federal Correctional Complex, Butner|FCI Butner Low]].<ref>\"[http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Eric&Middle=Franklin&LastName=Rosser&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 Eric Franklin Rosser].\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/67kL6o5sH?url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction%3DNameSearch%26needingMoreList%3Dfalse%26FirstName%3DEric%26Middle%3DFranklin%26LastName%3DRosser%26Race%3DU%26Sex%3DU%26Age%3D%26x%3D0%26y%3D0 Archive]). [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]. Retrieved on May 18, 2012.</ref> He was released on January 13, 2017.\n\n==Release and new charges==\nIn July 2017, Rosser was caught watching child pornography as he fled [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] on a bus, with $10,000 strapped to each of his legs, a bag with $50,000, and $1000 worth of cannabis. He pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]]. He admitted that he was fleeing federal probation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRosser pleaded guilty to accessing the internet with intent to view child pornography after signing a plea agreement with prosecutors in October 2018.\n\nAccording to court documents filed by federal prosecutors, Rosser was riding on a bus from [[Butte, Montana|Butte]] to [[Billings, Montana|Billings]] in July 2017 when another man noticed child pornography on his screen. When the man approached Rosser about it, he reportedly said, \"Leave me alone. I know I have a problem\", according to court documents.\n\nThe fellow passenger called Billings police to the bus station, and when they arrived, Rosser admitted to looking at the images of young girls engaging in sexually explicit conduct. Police also found he had $10,000 in cash strapped to each leg, along with $50,000 in cash in his luggage and approximately $1,000 worth of marijuana, which he told police he purchased for personal use, according to court records.\n\nRosser additionally admitted to violating his probation conditions and fleeing federal supervision in Washington state, court documents say. He said he had emptied his bank account and fled to avoid going back to prison. \n\nOn Tuesday, Rosser told U.S. Magistrate Judge Jeremiah Lynch he did not dispute any of the information brought forth by federal prosecutors. Lynch said he would be sentenced to a minimum of 10 years and may be on supervised release for the rest of his life following the prison term. \n\nHis sentencing was set for January 17, 2019.<ref> https://missoulian.com/news/crime/man-found-watching-child-porn-on-montana-bus-with-k/article_317217dd-329f-5512-8405-0fe28acada1f.html </ref>\nOn February 21, 2020, Rosser was sentenced to ten years in prison, and to permanent supervision if he is ever released.<ref name=\":0\">https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/crime-and-courts/former-mellencamp-pianist-gets-prison-again-this-time-for-watching/article_c137b13c-4daa-5833-91f4-79ed78a62b01.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Perry, J.J. \"[http://www.heraldtimesonline.com/stories/1999/05/21/scene.990521_D3_JJP14157.sto Eric Rosser].\" ''[[Herald-Times]]''. May 21, 1999.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosser, Eric Franklin}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Thailand]]\n[[Category:People extradited to the United States]]\n[[Category:American pornographers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: bachelors degree \u2192 bachelor's degree, masters degree \u2192 master's degree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Franklin_Rosser"}
{"title_page": "Pahan Silu", "text_new": "{{See also|Pahan (disambiguation){{!}}Pahan}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Pahan Silu\n| image                 = Pahansilu2.JPG\n| caption            = \n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Michigan]], United States\n| genre               = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]]\n| years_active        = 2002 &ndash; present\n| label               = Pahan Silu Entertainment\n| associated_acts     = \n| website                 = [http://www.pahansilu.com www.pahansilu.com]\n| current_members     = [[Priyan Weerappuli]]<br>Venura Jayasekera<br>Lochana Talagala<br>Shirantha Kannangara\n}}\n'''''Pahan Silu''''' (which roughly translates to \"dancing candlelight\" from its original [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]], one of the three primary languages spoken on the island of [[Sri Lanka]]) is the name of a band formed in late 2002 by American-born musician [[Priyan Weerappuli]].\n\nPahan Silu began performing publicly at the April 2003 [[Sinhala New Year|Sri Lankan New Year]] celebration held in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and within two years, had begun performing their original compositions alongside those of classically trained Sri Lankan musicians - including Sangeet [[Nipun]] [[Sanath Nandasiri]] during his 2005 tour of the United States.  In addition to Nandasiri, they have also performed with [[Walter Fernando]] (brother of the late [[baila]] singer [[M.S. Fernando]]), and female vocalist [[Malkanthi Nandasiri]], during their tours of the United States.\n\nThe success Pahan Silu has enjoyed in recent years is owed primarily to the unique sound they have introduced to Sri Lankan music.  In an era when many Sri Lankan performers (including pop-R&B duo [[Bathiya and Santhush]]) have drawn influence from urban and techno musicians in England and the United States, Pahan Silu turned, instead, to the rich, blended, harmonies of [[Africa]]n music, and the acoustic rhythms of [[Latin America]]n music.\n\nTheir first single, \"Sirip\u0101da\", a song recounting the story of a group of friends who climb to the top of [[Sri Pada|Sr\u012b P\u0101da]] (also referred to as [[Adam's Peak]]) thru its dense pre-dawn fog, debuted on March 10, 2007 on [[Asian Broadcasting Company|The Asian Broadcasting Company's]] Sri Lankan affiliate [[Hiru FM]].\n\nTheir second single, \"M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8\", a song which describes Priyan's memory of the 2000 concert given by [[Pandith Amaradeva]] in the US, debuted on December 2, 2007 simultaneously on both the [[BBC]] and [[SLBC]].\n\nIn December 2008, Pahan Silu collaborated with the Sudanese Gospel Choir to perform in a special edition of SirasaTV's \"Looks Like\" program broadcast in early 2009 which included the premier of their single \"Yala\".\n\nAmong others, founding member Priyan Weerappuli credits [[Ladysmith Black Mambazo]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Papa Wemba]], Pandith Amaradeva, [[John Denver]], [[Clarence Wijewardane]], [[James Taylor]], [[Carlos Vives]], [[Juanes]] and [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]] as the influences behind Pahan Silu's sound.\n\n==Discography==\n'''Dayani's Theme''' (Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''Sirip\u0101da''' (S.Fernando/Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8''' (Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''Mihirak\u012b Oba''' (Kannangara/Weerappuli 2008)\n\n'''Yala''' (Weerappuli 2009)\n\n'''Gamanak Yanowa''' (Weerappuli 2011)\n\n'''Iura Dhige''' (Weerappuli/Jayasekera 2011)\n\n'''Lelena Pahan Silu''' (Weerappuli 2012)\n\n==Additional Notes==\n* The name \"''Pahan Silu''\" was given to the group by Priyan's father, and was drawn from a passage in the \"[[Guththila Kavyaya|Guttila]]\" story written by V\u00e0ethth\u00e0eve Himi - later incorporated into the song \"''Ru Rase Andhina Lese''\" by lyricist Sisira S\u00e9naratne.\n* Priyan composed the music for the song \"Siripada\" based on his memory of a hike upon Virginia's \"[[Old Rag Mountain]]\" - he has yet to visit Sri Lanka's fabled peak.\n* The song \"''M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8''\" was written by Priyan for a BBC tribute celebrating the 80th birthday of Sri Lankan artist Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]].\n* The song \"''Yala''\" was written about a hike Priyan took in the Blue Ridge Mountains of northern Virginia - he has yet to visit Sri Lanka's famed national park.\n\n==Members (In Alphabetical Order)==\n'''Current Members (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nVenura Jayasekera (Acoustic Guitar, Bass Guitar, Keyboard, Vocals)\n\nShirantha Kannangara (Vocals)\n\nPramod Nugaliyadda (Sound Engineer)\n\nLochana Talagala (Acoustic Guitar, Bass Guitar)\n\nPriyan Weerappuli (Acoustic Guitar, Electric Guitar, Bass Guitar, Keyboard, Percussion, [[Music of Sri Lanka|Thamm\u00e1tama]], Vocals)\n\n'''Guest Performers (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nUmanga deSilva (Acoustic Guitar, Vocals)\n\nJacob Falk (Djembe, Congas)\n\nBrian Rishi Fernando (Acoustic Guitar)\n\nShripal Fernando (Vocals)\n\nPraveen Fernandopulle (Vocals)\n\nChinthana Herath (Flute, Violin)\n\nK. Jayawardene ([[Tabla]])\n\nRuwan Jayaweera (Vocals)\n\nSamadhi Liyanage (Vocals)\n\nChandratilaka Liyanarachchi (Vocals)\n\nDeepthi Weerappuli (Keyboard)\n\nSujit Weerasinghe (Percussion)\n\n'''Alumni (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nSanjaya Abeysirigunawardena (Vocals)\n\nChinthaka Weerappuli ([[Tabla]])\n\n==External Links and Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020501/http://www.sinhalajukebox.org/cgi-bin/songs.cgi?action=ShowTracks&artist=A695&compose= Pahan Silu Instrumentals on Sinhala Jukebox]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediaselector/ondemand/sinhala/meta/dps/2007/12/071205_himaw1?bgc=003399&lang=si&nbram=1&nbwm=1&ms3=4&ms_javascript=true&bbcws=1&size=au  BBC Broadcast Link for the Himaw Arana program that featured the music of Pahan Silu.]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==External Media Resources==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RdbweuKp_q0 '''Dayani's Theme''' Video on YouTube]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g8oGPBTyE9M '''Siripada''' Video on YouTube]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EE6cqQ2Vluo '''Mihiraki Oba''' Video on YouTube]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MYL5Eth52vM '''Yala''' Video on YouTube]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sinhala-language poets]]\n[[Category:Entertainment in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan musicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Pahan (disambiguation){{!}}Pahan}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Pahan Silu\n| image                 = Pahansilu2.JPG\n| caption            = \n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Michigan]], United States\n| genre               = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]]\n| years_active        = 2002 &ndash; present\n| label               = Pahan Silu Entertainment\n| associated_acts     = \n| website                 = [http://www.pahansilu.com www.pahansilu.com]\n| current_members     = [[Priyan Weerappuli]]<br>Venura Jayasekera<br>Lochana Talagala<br>Shirantha Kannangara\n}}\n'''''Pahan Silu''''' (which roughly translates to \"dancing candlelight\" from its original [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]], one of the three primary languages spoken on the island of [[Sri Lanka]]) is the name of a band formed in late 2002 by American-born musician [[Priyan Weerappuli]].\n\nPahan Silu began performing publicly at the April 2003 [[Sinhala New Year|Sri Lankan New Year]] celebration held in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and within two years, had begun performing their original compositions alongside those of classically trained Sri Lankan musicians - including Sangeet [[Nipun]] [[Sanath Nandasiri]] during his 2005 tour of the United States.  In addition to Nandasiri, they have also performed with [[Walter Fernando]] (brother of the late [[baila]] singer [[M.S. Fernando]]), and female vocalist [[Malkanthi Nandasiri]], during their tours of the United States.\n\nThe success Pahan Silu has enjoyed in recent years is owed primarily to the unique sound they have introduced to Sri Lankan music.  In an era when many Sri Lankan performers (including pop-R&B duo [[Bathiya and Santhush]]) have drawn influence from urban and techno musicians in England and the United States, Pahan Silu turned, instead, to the rich, blended, harmonies of [[Africa]]n music, and the acoustic rhythms of [[Latin America]]n music.\n\nTheir first single, \"Sirip\u0101da\", a song recounting the story of a group of friends who climb to the top of [[Sri Pada|Sr\u012b P\u0101da]] (also referred to as [[Adam's Peak]]) thru its dense pre-dawn fog, debuted on March 10, 2007 on [[Asian Broadcasting Company|The Asian Broadcasting Company's]] Sri Lankan affiliate [[Hiru FM]].\n\nTheir second single, \"M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8\", a song which describes Priyan's memory of the 2000 concert given by [[Pandith Amaradeva]] in the US, debuted on December 2, 2007 simultaneously on both the [[BBC]] and [[SLBC]].\n\nIn December 2008, Pahan Silu collaborated with the Sudanese Gospel Choir to perform in a special edition of SirasaTV's \"Looks Like\" program broadcast in early 2009 which included the premier of their single \"Yala\".\n\nAmong others, founding member Priyan Weerappuli credits [[Ladysmith Black Mambazo]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Papa Wemba]], Pandith Amaradeva, [[John Denver]], [[Clarence Wijewardane]], [[James Taylor]], [[Carlos Vives]], [[Juanes]] and [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]] as the influences behind Pahan Silu's sound.\n\n==Discography==\n'''Dayani's Theme''' (Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''Sirip\u0101da''' (S.Fernando/Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8''' (Weerappuli 2007)\n\n'''Mihirak\u012b Oba''' (Kannangara/Weerappuli 2008)\n\n'''Yala''' (Weerappuli 2009)\n\n'''Gamanak Yanowa''' (Weerappuli 2011)\n\n'''Iura Dhige''' (Weerappuli/Jayasekera 2011)\n\n'''Lelena Pahan Silu''' (Weerappuli 2012)\n\n==Additional Notes==\n* The name \"''Pahan Silu''\" was given to the group by Priyan's father, and was drawn from a passage in the \"[[Guththila Kavyaya|Guttila]]\" story written by V\u00e0ethth\u00e0eve Himi - later incorporated into the song \"''Ru Rase Andhina Lese''\" by lyricist Sisira S\u00e9naratne.\n* Priyan composed the music for the song \"Siripada\" based on his memory of a hike upon Virginia's \"[[Old Rag Mountain]]\" - he has yet to visit Sri Lanka's fabled peak.\n* The song \"''M\u012bray\u00e8n \u00c8ha Thal\u00e8''\" was written by Priyan for a BBC tribute celebrating the 80th birthday of Sri Lankan artist Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]].\n* The song \"''Yala''\" was written about a hike Priyan took in the Blue Ridge Mountains of northern Virginia - he has yet to visit Sri Lanka's famed national park.\n\n==Members (In Alphabetical Order)==\n'''Current Members (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nVenura Jayasekera (Acoustic Guitar, Bass Guitar, Keyboard, Vocals)\n\nShirantha Kannangara (Vocals)\n\nPramod Nugaliyadda (Sound Engineer)\n\nLochana Talagala (Acoustic Guitar, Bass Guitar)\n\nPriyan Weerappuli (Acoustic Guitar, Electric Guitar, Bass Guitar, Keyboard, Percussion, [[Music of Sri Lanka|Thamm\u00e1tama]], Vocals)\n\n'''Guest Performers (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nUmanga deSilva (Acoustic Guitar, Vocals)\n\nJacob Falk (Djembe, Congas)\n\nBrian Rishi Fernando (Acoustic Guitar)\n\nShripal Fernando (Vocals)\n\nPraveen Fernandopulle (Vocals)\n\nChinthana Herath (Flute, Violin)\n\nK. Jayawardene ([[Tabla]])\n\nRuwan Jayaweera (Vocals)\n\nSamadhi Liyanage (Vocals)\n\nChandratilaka Liyanarachchi (Vocals)\n\nDeepthi Weerappuli (Keyboard)\n\nSujit Weerasinghe (Percussion)\n\n'''Alumni (In Alphabetical Order)'''\n\nSanjaya Abeysirigunawardena (Vocals)\n\nChinthaka Weerappuli ([[Tabla]])\n\n==External Links and Sources==\n*