{"title_page": "Victoria Jordanova", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n'''Victoria Jordanova''', born Viktorija (Vita) Pop Jordanova in the former Yugoslavia in 1952, is a composer/performer and media artist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scrc.gmu.edu/finding_aids/jordanova.html|title=Guide to the Victoria Jordanova music collection, 1993-1996Victoria Jordanova music C0111|website=scrc.gmu.edu|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>.  She is the creative director, curator, producer and the sound editor for [http://www.arpaviva.org/ ArpaViva] label she founded in 2003.\n\n==Career==\nAs a composer, virtuoso harpist, and pianist, Victoria Jordanova melds experimental techniques, electronics and improvisation with her classical music education.  Recordings of her music were published by [[Composers Recordings, Inc.|Composer's Recordings Inc.]], [[Innova Recordings|Innova]], and ArpaViva labels. Jordanova wrote music for ensembles such as [[The California EAR Unit]],<ref>{{cite news |title=California EAR Unit returns to start a lively conversation |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/247245291.html?dids=247245291:247245291&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+27%2C+2002&author=Josef+Woodard&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=MUSIC+REVIEW%3B+California+EAR+Unit+returns+to+start+a+lively+conversation&pqatl=google |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 27, 2002 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 | first=Josef | last=Woodard}}</ref>  [http://www.zeitgeistnewmusic.org/ Zeitgeist], [[Bang on a Can|Bang On The Can All Stars]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Bang on a Can Uptown Cultivates Crossover |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/23/arts/music-review-bang-on-a-can-uptown-cultivates-crossover.html?scp=691&sq=victoria+fire&st=nyt |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= May 23, 1995|accessdate=August 2, 2010 | first=Allan | last=Kozinn}}</ref> [http://www.singers.com/choral/creativevoices.html Creative Voices], and CurvedAir.  Her music was included in \"The Composer-Performer 40 Years of Discovery\",  [[Composers Recordings, Inc.|Composer's Recordings Inc.]] 40th Anniversary Anthology of American Music in 1994. Her solo CD  \"Requiem for Bosnia and Other Works\"  was selected as one of the 10 best classical recordings of the year by [[Tim Page (music critic)|Tim Page]] in New York NewsDay in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 10 Seven Lists From Seven Critics |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/101904470.html?dids=101904470:101904470&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+24%2C+1994&author=Jack+Mathews.+Linda+Winer.+Ira+Robbins.+John+Anderson.&pub=Newsday+%28Combined+editions%29&desc=The+Top+10+Seven+Lists+From+Seven+Critics&pqatl=google |work=[[Newsday]] |date=December 24, 1994 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nWith ArpaViva Victoria Jordanova published first ever recording of [[John Cage]]'s \"Postcard From Heaven\" for 1-20 harps in 2007.  Harp parts were played by Jordanova herself while Cage's ossia vocal part was performed by [[Pamela Z]].  ArpaViva releases also include DVD \"[http://www.panopticon.us/index.html Panopticon]\" a film based on a live performance by Victoria Jordanova and California EAR Unit in the Bing Theater ([[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]) on November 25, 2002. \"Panopticon\" is an interdisciplinary piece exploring \"surveillance society\", and performers include California EAR Unit, Victoria Jordanova, and Jeffery Atik. This erformance was directed by [[Relja Penezic]] and released in 2003, distributed by [[Cinema Guild]] of New York. The 2007 CD \"In a Landscape\" is dedicated to music for electric and amplified harp, and the 2010 album \"New York Love Songs\", named after song cycle Jordanova wrote in 1997 in New York City, also includes pieces by [[Charles Ives]], John Cage, [[Frederic Rzewski]], and Ashley Wang, performed by [[Jenny Q. Chai]].\n\n==Education==\nVictoria Jordanova holds B.A. from [[Michigan State University]]. After graduating from Michigan State University, she was awarded the French government fellowship for special graduate studies in Paris. While in Paris, she was an Artist-in-Residence at the Cit\u00e9 International des Arts. Following her studies in Paris, Jordanova studied at the Moscow Conservatory and then returned to the United States with a Langley Fellowship at New York University where she completed an M.A. in Musicology.\n\n==Personal life==\nToday, Victoria Jordanova lives and works in Los Angeles, California.\n\n== Archival Collections ==\nA collection of Jordanova's donated materials is housed at the [https://scrc.gmu.edu George Mason University Special Collections Research Center].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.victoriajordanova.com/ Victoria Jordanova's website]\n* [http://www.arpaviva.org/ ArpaViva Foundation Inc.]\n* [http://www.panopticon.us/ Panopticon]\n* [http://newmusicbox.org/page.nmbx?id=66hf03 Jordanova on \"Requiem for Bosnia\"]\n* [http://www.innova.mu/artist1.asp?skuID=207 \"Outer Circles\" Album]\n* [http://www.newworldrecords.org/album.cgi?rm=view&album_id=17535/ \"Dance to Sleep\" Album]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordanova, Victoria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Serbian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n'''Victoria Jordanova''', born Viktorija (Vita) Pop Jordanova in Serbia in 1952, is a composer/performer and media artist.  She is the creative director, curator, producer and the sound editor for [http://www.arpaviva.org/ ArpaViva] label she founded in 2003.\n\n==Career==\nAs a composer, virtuoso harpist, and pianist Victoria Jordanova melds experimental techniques, electronics and improvisation with her classical music education.  Recordings of her music were published by [[Composers Recordings, Inc.|Composer's Recordings Inc.]], [[Innova Recordings|Innova]], and ArpaViva labels.  Jordanova wrote music for ensembles such as [[The California EAR Unit]],<ref>{{cite news |title=California EAR Unit returns to start a lively conversation |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/247245291.html?dids=247245291:247245291&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+27%2C+2002&author=Josef+Woodard&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=MUSIC+REVIEW%3B+California+EAR+Unit+returns+to+start+a+lively+conversation&pqatl=google |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 27, 2002 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 | first=Josef | last=Woodard}}</ref>  [http://www.zeitgeistnewmusic.org/ Zeitgeist], [[Bang on a Can|Bang On The Can All Stars]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Bang on a Can Uptown Cultivates Crossover |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/23/arts/music-review-bang-on-a-can-uptown-cultivates-crossover.html?scp=691&sq=victoria+fire&st=nyt |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= May 23, 1995|accessdate=August 2, 2010 | first=Allan | last=Kozinn}}</ref> [http://www.singers.com/choral/creativevoices.html Creative Voices], and CurvedAir.  Her music was included in \"The Composer-Performer 40 Years of Discovery\",  [[Composers Recordings, Inc.|Composer's Recordings Inc.]] 40th Anniversary Anthology of American Music in 1994. Her solo CD  \"Requiem for Bosnia and Other Works\"  was selected as one of the 10 best classical recordings of the year by [[Tim Page (music critic)|Tim Page]] in New York NewsDay in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 10 Seven Lists From Seven Critics |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/101904470.html?dids=101904470:101904470&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+24%2C+1994&author=Jack+Mathews.+Linda+Winer.+Ira+Robbins.+John+Anderson.&pub=Newsday+%28Combined+editions%29&desc=The+Top+10+Seven+Lists+From+Seven+Critics&pqatl=google |work=[[Newsday]] |date=December 24, 1994 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nWith ArpaViva Victoria Jordanova published first ever recording of [[John Cage]]'s \"Postcard From Heaven\" for 1-20 harps in 2007.  Harp parts were played by Jordanova herself while Cage's ossia vocal part was performed by [[Pamela Z]].  ArpaViva releases also include DVD \"[http://www.panopticon.us/index.html Panopticon]\" a film based on a live performance by Victoria Jordanova and California EAR Unit in the Bing Theater ([[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]) on November 25, 2002, \"Panopticon\" is an interdisciplinary piece exploring \"surveillance society\", performers include California EAR Unit, Victoria Jordanova, and Jeffery Atik, directed by [[Relja Penezic]], released in 2003 distributed by [[Cinema Guild]] of New York. 2007 CD \"In a Landscape\" is dedicated to music for electric and amplified harp, and 2010 album \"New York Love Songs\", named after song cycle Jordanova wrote in 1997 in New York City also includes pieces by [[Charles Ives]], John Cage, [[Frederic Rzewski]], and Ashley Wang, performed by [[Jenny Q. Chai]].\n\n==Education==\nVictoria Jordanova holds BA from [[Michigan State University]].  She received the Langley Fellowship to [[New York University]] where she received her M.A. in Musicology.  She was awarded the French government fellowship for special graduate studies in Paris.  While in Paris, she was also an Artist-in-Residence at the Cite International des Arts.\n\n==Personal life==\nToday, Victoria Jordanova lives and works in Los Angeles, California.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.victoriajordanova.com/ Victoria Jordanova's website]\n* [http://www.arpaviva.org/ ArpaViva Foundation Inc.]\n* [http://www.panopticon.us/ Panopticon]\n* [http://newmusicbox.org/page.nmbx?id=66hf03 Jordanova on \"Requiem for Bosnia\"]\n* [http://www.innova.mu/artist1.asp?skuID=207 \"Outer Circles\" Album]\n* [http://www.newworldrecords.org/album.cgi?rm=view&album_id=17535/ \"Dance to Sleep\" Album]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordanova, Victoria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Serbian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "SCRCgmuReferenceStudent2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed grammatical mistakes and added an archival collections section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Jordanova"}
{"title_page": "Imagery", "text_new": "{{about|the literary technique}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n'''Imagery''', in a literary text, is an author's use of vivid and descriptive language to add depth to their work. Sensory imagery appeals to human [[senses]] to deepen the reader's understanding of the work. Powerful forms of imagery engage all of the senses. Like bananas\n\n==Forms== \nThere are five major types of sensory imagery, each corresponding to a sense, feeling, action, or reaction:\n\n*'''Visual imagery''' pertains to graphics, visual scenes, pictures, or the sense of sight.\n*'''Auditory imagery''' pertains to sounds, noises, music, or the sense of hearing. (This kind of imagery may come in the form of [[onomatopoeia]]).\n*'''Olfactory imagery''' pertains to odors, aromas, scents, or the sense of smell.\n*'''Gustatory imagery''' pertains to flavors or the sense of taste.\n*'''Tactile imagery''' pertains to physical textures or the sense of touch.\n\nOther types of imagery include:\n\n*'''Kinesthetic imagery''' pertains to movements.\n*'''Organic imagery / subjective imagery''', pertains to personal experiences of a character's body, including emotion and the senses of hunger, thirst, fatigue, and pain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poetics of Robert Frost: Examples|url=http://www.frostfriends.org/imagery.html|publisher=Friends of Robert Frost|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>\n*'''[[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenological]]''', pertains to the mental conception of an item as opposed to the physical version.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite IEP |url-id=imagery |title=Imagery and Imagination}}\n*  {{citation |last=Thomas |first=Nigel J.T |title=Mental Imagery |url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mental-imagery/ |work=[[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |editor-last= Zalta |editor-first=Edward N. |date=Winter 2011}}\n<!-- *[http://www.readprint.com/article-5 http://www.readprint.com/article-5] -->\n\n{{Fiction writing}}\n\n[[Category:Fiction]]\n[[Category:Style (fiction)]]\n[[Category:Literature]]\n[[Category:Narrative techniques]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the literary technique}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n'''Imagery''', in a literary text, is an author's use of vivid and descriptive language to add depth to their work. Sensory imagery appeals to human [[senses]] to deepen the reader's understanding of the work. Powerful forms of imagery engage all of the senses.\n\n==Forms== \nThere are five major types of sensory imagery, each corresponding to a sense, feeling, action, or reaction:\n\n*'''Visual imagery''' pertains to graphics, visual scenes, pictures, or the sense of sight.\n*'''Auditory imagery''' pertains to sounds, noises, music, or the sense of hearing. (This kind of imagery may come in the form of [[onomatopoeia]]).\n*'''Olfactory imagery''' pertains to odors, aromas, scents, or the sense of smell.\n*'''Gustatory imagery''' pertains to flavors or the sense of taste.\n*'''Tactile imagery''' pertains to physical textures or the sense of touch.\n\nOther types of imagery include:\n\n*'''Kinesthetic imagery''' pertains to movements.\n*'''Organic imagery / subjective imagery''', pertains to personal experiences of a character's body, including emotion and the senses of hunger, thirst, fatigue, and pain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poetics of Robert Frost: Examples|url=http://www.frostfriends.org/imagery.html|publisher=Friends of Robert Frost|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>\n*'''[[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenological]]''', pertains to the mental conception of an item as opposed to the physical version.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite IEP |url-id=imagery |title=Imagery and Imagination}}\n*  {{citation |last=Thomas |first=Nigel J.T |title=Mental Imagery |url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mental-imagery/ |work=[[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |editor-last= Zalta |editor-first=Edward N. |date=Winter 2011}}\n<!-- *[http://www.readprint.com/article-5 http://www.readprint.com/article-5] -->\n\n{{Fiction writing}}\n\n[[Category:Fiction]]\n[[Category:Style (fiction)]]\n[[Category:Literature]]\n[[Category:Narrative techniques]]\n", "name_user": "96.8.248.38", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo on the last word)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imagery"}
{"title_page": "Larry Payne", "text_new": "[[File:I_AM_A_MAN_183.jpeg|thumbnail|A police officer, Leslie Dean Jones, beats a youth during the violence that erupted on March 28, 1968, in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. Larry Payne, the 16-year-old in the background, was killed by Jones later in the day.]]\n'''Larry Payne''' was a sixteen-year old African American teenager who was killed following a march in support of the [[Memphis Sanitation Strike]] on Thursday, March 28, 1968, in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Larry Payne|url=http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/larry-payne/|website=Civil Rights and Restorative Justice|publisher=Northwestern University School of Law|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> He was the only fatality on that day although the ''[[New Pittsburgh Courier]]'' reported 60 injured and 276 arrested.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ratcliff|first1=Robert M.|title=Memphis: King's Biggest Gamble--March Was Out of Hand Before It Even Started|work=New Pittsburgh Courier|date=April 6, 1968|ref=202493174}}</ref>\n \n[[Martin Luther King Jr.]] called Payne's mother, Lizzie Payne, on the phone to console her after her son's brutal death at the hands of Patrolman Leslie Dean Jones.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=83 year old mother grieves son's death|url=http://www.democraticunderground.com/discuss/duboard.php?az=view_all&address=367x9126|website=Commercial Appeal via Democratic Underground|publisher=Gannett|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Events leading up to Payne's death==\n\nConflicting accounts describe the looting that occurred in tandem with the march on Thursday March 28 1968 that led to a city-wide curfew and Mayor Loeb calling the Tennessese National Guard.\n\n==Payne's funeral==\n\nThere was a five-hour wake the day before the funeral on Monday, April 1, 1968.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Probe Killing of Memphis Youth|last=Special to the Daily Defender|date=April 1, 1968|work=Chicago Defender (Daily Edition)|}}</ref> Six hundred attended his funeral at [[Clayborn Temple]] on Tuesday, April 2, 1968.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news|title=600 Attend Funeral for Young Riot Victim|last=Reid|first=McCann|date=April 2, 1968|work=Chicago Defender (Daily Edition)|}}</ref> Striking sanitation workers, clergy members who supported the strike, and national television representatives were all in attendance as well as the students and faculty of Mitchell Road High School where Payne was enrolled prior to his death. Rev. B.T. Dumas, pastor of New Philadelphia Baptist Church gave the eulogy entitled \"Man Is Like Grass And Is Cut Down in Various Stages of Life.\" Surprisingly, Rev. Dumas made no reference to the unusual circumstances of Payne's death.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Payne's mother, Lizzie Mason Payne, had to be led from the church she was so full of grief. The Washington Post quoted her as saying: \"They killed you like a dog.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Memphis Riot Victim Buried|date=April 3, 1968|work= The Washington Post(Times Herald)|}}</ref>\n\n== Events after Payne's death ==\nKing planned to visit Payne's mother during his next visit to Memphis, but was killed before the visit could occur.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> He was [[Assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.|assassinated]] seven days later, on April 4, 1968, when he returned to Memphis in an effort to hold a peaceful march unmarred by looting and violence.\n\nAfter Payne's death, Lizzie Payne, his mother, moved to [[Flint, Michigan]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Memphis Sanitation Strike]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.commercialappeal.com/opinion/local/my-thoughts-whither-larry-payne-civil-rights-and-hallowed-grounds-2cb16255-bae3-0b83-e053-0100007fe8-370348011.html \"My thoughts: Wither Larry Payne, civil rights and hallowed grounds?\"] Commercial Appeal, February 27, 2016.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RxRbItaeKaE Interview with Larry Payne's mother, brother, and sister] (Recorded: March 2, 2010)\n*[http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/6152791/fbi-to-reopen-memphis-civil-rights-era-cold-case FBI to Re-Open Memphis Civil Rights era cold case] (WMC Channel 5 News)\n*[https://hakimbe.bandcamp.com/track/for-larry-payne For Larry Payne] (a poem commissioned by Fusion Theatre Company and written by Hakim Bellamy, November 9, 2013)\n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Payne, Larry}}\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:1968 labor disputes and strikes]]\n[[Category:History of Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests in the United States]]\n[[Category:Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n[[Category:Labor disputes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1968 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in the United States]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Victims of human rights abuses|Police]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People shot dead by law enforcement officers in the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n{{civil-rights-movement-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:I_AM_A_MAN_183.jpeg|thumbnail|A police officer, Leslie Dean Jones, beats a youth during the violence that erupted on March 28, 1968, in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. Larry Payne, the 16-year-old in the background, was killed by Jones later in the day.]]\n'''Larry Payne''' was a sixteen-year old African American teenager who was killed following a march in support of the [[Memphis Sanitation Strike]] on Thursday, March 28, 1968, in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Larry Payne|url=http://nuweb9.neu.edu/civilrights/larry-payne/|website=Civil Rights and Restorative Justice|publisher=Northwestern University School of Law|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> He was the only fatality on that day although the ''[[New Pittsburgh Courier]]'' reported 60 injured and 276 arrested.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ratcliff|first1=Robert M.|title=Memphis: King's Biggest Gamble--March Was Out of Hand Before It Even Started|work=New Pittsburgh Courier|date=April 6, 1968|ref=202493174}}</ref>\n \n[[Martin Luther King Jr.]] called Payne's mother, Lizzie Payne, on the phone to console her after her son's brutal death at the hands of Patrolman Leslie Dean Jones.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=83 year old mother grieves son's death|url=http://www.democraticunderground.com/discuss/duboard.php?az=view_all&address=367x9126|website=Commercial Appeal via Democratic Underground|publisher=Gannett|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Events leading up to Payne's death==\n\nConflicting accounts describe the looting that occurred in tandem with the march on Thursday March 28 1968 that led to a city-wide curfew and Mayor Loeb calling the Tennessese National Guard.\n\n==Payne's funeral==\n\nThere was a five hour wake the day before the funeral on Monday, April 1, 1968.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Probe Killing of Memphis Youth|last=Special to the Daily Defender|date=April 1, 1968|work=Chicago Defender (Daily Edition)|}}</ref> Six hundred attended his funeral at [[Clayborn Temple]] on Tuesday, April 2, 1968.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news|title=600 Attend Funeral for Young Riot Victim|last=Reid|first=McCann|date=April 2, 1968|work=Chicago Defender (Daily Edition)|}}</ref> Striking sanitation workers, clergy members who supported the strike, and national television representatives were all in attendance as well as the students and faculty of Mitchell Road High School where Payne was enrolled prior to his death. Rev. B.T. Dumas, pastor of New Philadelphia Baptist Church gave the eulogy entitled \"Man Is Like Grass And Is Cut Down in Various Stages of Life.\" Surprisingly, Rev. Dumas made no reference to the unusual circumstances of Payne's death.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Payne's mother, Lizzie Mason Payne, had to be led from the church she was so full of grief. The Washington Post quoted her as saying: \"They killed you like a dog.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Memphis Riot Victim Buried|date=April 3, 1968|work= The Washington Post(Times Herald)|}}</ref>\n\n== Events after Payne's death ==\nKing planned to visit Payne's mother during his next visit to Memphis, but was killed before the visit could occur.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> He was [[Assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.|assassinated]] seven days later, on April 4, 1968, when he returned to Memphis in an effort to hold a peaceful march unmarred by looting and violence.\n\nAfter Payne's death, Lizzie Payne, his mother, moved to [[Flint, Michigan]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Memphis Sanitation Strike]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.commercialappeal.com/opinion/local/my-thoughts-whither-larry-payne-civil-rights-and-hallowed-grounds-2cb16255-bae3-0b83-e053-0100007fe8-370348011.html \"My thoughts: Wither Larry Payne, civil rights and hallowed grounds?\"] Commercial Appeal, February 27, 2016.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RxRbItaeKaE Interview with Larry Payne's mother, brother, and sister] (Recorded: March 2, 2010)\n*[http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/6152791/fbi-to-reopen-memphis-civil-rights-era-cold-case FBI to Re-Open Memphis Civil Rights era cold case] (WMC Channel 5 News)\n*[https://hakimbe.bandcamp.com/track/for-larry-payne For Larry Payne] (a poem commissioned by Fusion Theatre Company and written by Hakim Bellamy, November 9, 2013)\n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Payne, Larry}}\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:1968 labor disputes and strikes]]\n[[Category:History of Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests in the United States]]\n[[Category:Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n[[Category:Labor disputes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1968 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in the United States]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Victims of human rights abuses|Police]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People shot dead by law enforcement officers in the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-cri