{"title_page": "University of the Sciences", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = University of the Sciences\n| motto        = ''Nosse haec omnia salus est''\n| mottoeng = ''To know all this is health''\n| established  = 1821\n| type         = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment    = Approx. $170 million\n| president    = Paul Katz, MD\n| undergrad    = 1,231\n| postgrad     = 1,000\n| city         = [[Philadelphia]]\n| state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = [[Urbanization|Urban]]\n| free_label   = Athletics\n| free         = 12 varsity teams, 17 intramural clubs\n| mascot       = Devils, \"Drake the Devil\"\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.usciences.edu}}\n| footnotes    = \n| image_name   = University of the Sciences logo.png\n| faculty      = 177\n| colors       = Maroon and slate {{color box|#460017}}&nbsp;{{color box|#B7B7B7}}\n| affiliations = [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[NCAA]], [[Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference|CACC]], [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]]\n}}\n'''University of the Sciences''' ('''USciences'''), officially the '''University of the Sciences in Philadelphia''', is a private university in [[Philadelphia]], [[United States]]. USciences offers bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees in [[pharmacy]] and other health-related disciplines. USciences was established in 1821 as the '''Philadelphia College of Pharmacy''', to become the first pharmacy college in the nation.\n\n==History==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2011}}\n{{advert|section|date=December 2011}}\n}}\n[[File:University of the Sciences.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Campus entrance]]\nThe history of University of the Sciences began when 68 Philadelphia apothecaries met in [[Carpenters' Hall]] in 1821 to establish improved scientific standards and to train more competent apprentices and students. They sought to enhance their vocation, as well as protect public welfare. Nearly a year later, they organized and incorporated the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy (PCP), the first college of pharmacy in the nation. \n\nToday, the university has 52 degree-granting programs in three colleges. Its more than 2,200 students have enrolled in premier programs in the health sciences, ranging across pharmacy with its direct entry doctoral program to pre-med to physical therapy to healthcare business and health policy. Students study almost the entire range of the health sciences in one of its three colleges:\n\n* Philadelphia College of Pharmacy \u2014 North America's first school of pharmacy and the start of the University, graduates the pharmacists and scientists who deliver and discover the healthcare innovations that advance patient care.\n* Samson College of Health Sciences \u2014 educates the vital healthcare professionals who add immeasurably to the quality of life at each step\u2014from prevention to diagnosis to recovery of the patient care continuum.\n* Misher College of Arts and Sciences \u2014 provides a specialized undergraduate foundation for the sciences, with research and discovery at its core, for students seeking advanced degrees to lead in the basic and applied health sciences and serve humanity.\n\nAfter its conception in 1821, the college began to grow in enrollment, curriculum, and stature. Although matriculation was originally limited to men, the college became coeducational in 1876, and issued the first pharmacy degree to a woman in the United States, Dr. [[Susan Hayhurst]], in 1883.<ref name=Contributions>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B3dZEmPUoBcC&lpg=PA10&pg=PA10 |title=American Women Pharmacists: Contributions to the Profession |last1=Henderson |first1=Metta Lou |last2=Worthen |first2=Dennis B. |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=9780789010926 |page=10 |date=8 March 2002 |accessdate=29 November 2016 |via=Google Books}}</ref> The college initially emphasized the biological and chemical sciences as mainstays of the curriculum in pharmacy but later instituted separate curricula in three other areas: bacteriology, biology and chemistry.\n\nIn 1921, the name of the institution was changed to Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science, with state authorization to grant not only the baccalaureate degree, but also the master's and doctorate in all four disciplines.\n\nAs the world of science continuously made advancements throughout the decades, the college evolved and expanded its curriculum to prepare students for the new wave of scientific breakthroughs. The college also enhanced the role of the humanities and social sciences in its science-based curricula. Primarily a commuter campus in its early days, the institution began to transform into one in which residential life and extracurricular activities played a larger role in student development.\n\nThe Commonwealth of Pennsylvania approved the institution's application for university status in February 1997. In recognition of the broad spectrum of new health and science programs introduced by the institution, the college changed its name to reflect the broader range of academic opportunities offered to its students. On July 1, 1998, Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science officially unveiled its new identity as University of the Sciences in Philadelphia.\n\nA brand update in 2010 refocused the University's messaging and logos. The overall name was simplified for marketing purposes to University of the Sciences in order to emphasize a national and global reach, while a new logo transitioned the USP acronym to USciences to address awareness issues. In addition, the tag line \u201cWhere science and healthcare converge\u201d was adopted to define both what the University is and what it is not.\n\nIn September 2017, the University launched a tuition reset for all students who enroll beginning in fall 2018. Undergraduate students will not pay more than $25,000 per year in tuition and general fee* for undergraduate coursework. And for those students who are accepted into one of the University's accelerated, 6-year doctoral programs in pharmacy, physical therapy, or occupational therapy, the University lowered and simplified the tuition and general fee*. The lower tuition is fixed for the student's academic career. *This pricing does NOT include room and board, health insurance, or any professional, clinical, or transportation fees.<ref>[http://www.usciences.edu/lowertuition \"The tuition equation just got easier\"], University of the Sciences website</ref>\n\n===Shaping the profession of pharmacy===\n[[William Procter, Jr.]], often described as \"the father of American pharmacy\", was a PCP professor from 1846\u20131874, as well as serving as an officer of the board. He and [[Daniel B. Smith]] were instrumental in the founding of the American Pharmaceutical Association, the national professional society of pharmacists, which was founded and organized in Philadelphia in 1852. It is now called the American Pharmacists Association (APhA), the first established and largest professional association of pharmacists in the United States. The more than 50,000 members of APhA include practicing pharmacists, pharmaceutical scientists, pharmacy students, pharmacy technicians and others interested in advancing the profession.\n\nIn 1868, John Maisch, PCP professor (1866\u20131893) and dean (1879\u20131893), proposed the creation of a pharmaceutical board to be appointed by the governor of each state and established the term \"registered pharmacist\". He shared his proposal with each governor and, by 1878, nine states had adopted pharmacy laws which licensed pharmacists. Every state now, of course, has a Board of Pharmacy which regulates the practice of pharmacy.\n\nStarted in 1820, the [[United States Pharmacopeia]] laid down the standards for manufacturing drugs. For more than a hundred years, PCP faculty members were instrumental in its development, serving as editors throughout many editions.\n\nIn 1825, the first periodical in the United States devoted to the art and science of pharmacy, the ''American Journal of Pharmacy'', was published by PCP.\n\nPCP professors Franklin Bache and [[George Bacon Wood|George B. Wood]] compiled a comprehensive commentary on drugs, ''The Dispensatory of the United States of America''. First published in 1833, the ''Dispensatory'' was authored and edited for more than a hundred years by successive generations of faculty at the college.\n\nIn 1885, PCP professor [[Joseph P. Remington]] published ''The Practice of Pharmacy'', which soon became established as the standard text in the field. Later renamed ''Remington: The Science and Practice of Pharmacy'', this comprehensive reference work remains widely used throughout the world. The 22nd edition was published in September 2012 jointly by [[Pharmaceutical Press]] and the University of the Sciences.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usciences.edu/aboutUSP/USPhistory.shtml| title=USP History}}</ref>\n\n===Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy===\nThe Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usciences.edu/about/marvin-samson-center-for-the-history-of-pharmacy/index.html|title=Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy \u2013 University of the Sciences|work=usciences.edu|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> is an integral part of the University of the Sciences in Philadelphia.  The center's mission is to serve as an educational, cultural and research resource for the university, pharmacy professionals, historians and the general public through its collections of artifacts, objects and records representative of all aspects of pharmacy, including the pharmacy college's history. Through changing exhibitions, tours and programs, the center aims to deepen appreciation of the past, present and future significance of the pharmacy industry in the broader social context and in the development of American life, especially in the city of Philadelphia and the surrounding region.\n\n===Campus expansion program===\nThe university doubled the size of the campus in 1998 when it acquired an adjacent, vacant industrial site. (This site was formerly the home of the original Breyers Ice Cream factory which closed its Philadelphia operation in the early 1990s.) BLT Architects designed the Athletic and Recreation Center (ARC) in August 2003. BLT Architects channeled the ambience of a traditional college campus through this building. ARC is situated between a new campus quad and a commuter parking lot. Its design features a 1,000 seat event gymnasium, recreation gymnasium, natatorium, fitness areas and a 1/10 mile indoor track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blta.com/#/3/0/0/12/|title=Home \u2013 BLTa|work=BLTa|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> The McNeil Science and Technology Center (McNeil STC) was officially dedicated September 2006. Additional building projects are being planned.\n\nThe McNeil Science and Technology Center houses many new classrooms, computer research rooms and teaching laboratories as well as the undergraduate and graduate programs in biology, bioinformatics/computer science and math/physics/statistics. The centerpiece of the center is a 400-seat auditorium equipped with modern audio/visual equipment.\n\nIn fall 2014, the University opened the Integrated Professional Education Complex (IPEX) and demonstrates USciences\u2019 commitment to preparing graduates for careers in the life sciences and health sciences professions. The 57,000-square-foot, three-story building showcases an integrated education model that permits students from several disciplines, including physician assistant studies, pharmacy, physical therapy, occupational therapy, exercise science, psychology and healthcare business and policy, to obtain traditional and hands-on experience. This integrated education model gives students an opportunity to fully understand its value in their everyday practice. IPEX combines innovative learning spaces and student lounge space with simulation labs, a clinical lab, mock patient exam rooms and conference rooms. It will also serve as a hub for students to study, interact and learn with and from one another. IPEX houses the provisionally accredited physician assistant studies graduate professional program. A green-roof system that emphasizes the University's commitment to the environment and sustainability, measures 20,000 square feet and will absorb nearly 15,000 gallons of water when fully saturated. IPEX earned three Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.\n\nIn 2019, the University opened the Living & Learning Commons, a mixed-use residence hall located at 46th Street and Woodland Avenue. The 426-bed facility also includes state-of-the-art classroom, retail, living, and learning spaces and sets the standards for dynamic living and learning communities for science and healthcare students. The building features double occupancy rooms, private bathrooms, laundry amenities on each residence floor, a study lounge and study spaces on each floor, multi-use classroom spaces, and two retail spaces. An open-air plaza is a welcoming feature open to the greater USciences community and neighbors.\n\n==Academics==\nUniversity of the Sciences in Philadelphia has over 30 degree-granting programs for students from which to choose. The University is composed of three colleges: the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, Samson College of Health Sciences''',''' and Misher College of Arts & Sciences.\n\n=== Exchange agreements ===\nThe university has an exchange agreement with the [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)]] that allows ten students from each university to take one course a semester at the other. The university also has an agreement with the [[New York University]] Study Abroad Program that will allow University of the Sciences students to study at NYU campuses in Asia, Africa and Europe for a semester or a year.\n\n===The J. W. England Library===\nThe Library of the University of the Sciences in Philadelphia was formed in 1821 at the second meeting of the Board of Trustees. Since its beginnings, the library has been considered one of the premier collections of pharmaceutical science in the country. In 1973, the library moved into its present quarters, the free-standing Joseph W. England Library. Small but specialized, the collection is particularly strong in pharmacy, pharmacognosy, pharmaceutics and foreign drug compendia. Other areas of specialization include toxicology, pharmacology and physical therapy. Contained in the Leopold Helfand Rare Book and Archives Room is a collection of seventeenth and eighteenth century botanicals, including a book once owned by Isaac Newton. Since the university and its graduates were fundamental to the building of the United States pharmaceutical industry, the university archives are of interest to anyone researching the origins of the pharmaceutical industry.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2016}}\n[[File:USciDevils.png|thumb|Official athletics logo.]]\nThe University of the Sciences (USciences) teams participate as a member of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'s [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]. The Devils are a member of the [[Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference]] (CACC). Men's sports include baseball, basketball, cross country, golf, tennis and track & field; while women's sports include basketball, cross country, softball, tennis, track & field and volleyball. The baseball team participates in the [[Bill Giles Invitational]] tournament for Division II teams in the Philadelphia area.\n\n==Alumni==\nUniversity of the Sciences has launched the careers of many innovative and pioneering individuals in the field of health care, including the founders of six of the world's leading pharmaceutical companies:\n* Dr. [[Susan Hayhurst]]  (Class of 1883) \u2013 longtime head of the pharmaceutical department at the [[Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia]] and the first woman to receive a pharmacy degree in the United States<ref name=Contributions/>\n\n=== Major pharmaceuticals ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2011}}\n* Sir [[Henry Wellcome]] (Class of 1874) \u2013 co-founder of Burroughs Wellcome and Company, which is now part of [[GlaxoSmithKline]].\n* [[Silas Mainville Burroughs (pharmacist)|Silas M. Burroughs]] (Class of 1877) \u2013 co-founder of Burroughs Wellcome and Company, which is now part of [[GlaxoSmithKline]].\n* [[Josiah K. Lilly Sr.]] (Class of 1882) \u2013 father of Eli Lilly ('07). President of [[Eli Lilly and Company]]. The company was founded by Josiah's father, [[Colonel Eli Lilly]].\n* [[Eli Lilly (industrialist)|Eli Lilly]] (Class of 1907) \u2013 president of Eli Lilly and Company. The company was founded by Eli's grandfather, [[Colonel Eli Lilly]].\n* [[Robert L. McNeil, Jr.]] (Class of 1938) \u2013 chairman and CEO of [[McNeil Laboratories]] Inc., now part of [[Johnson & Johnson]]. Campus building named after him.\n\n===Alumni contributions===\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2018}}\nUniversity of the Sciences alumni have also contributed to the [[invention]] of well-known products, \n* [[Hires Root Beer]] extract\n* [[Photocopier|Photocopy toner]] and electrographic [[ink]]s\n* [[Polyurethane]]s\n* [[Silicone]]-based adhesives\n* [[Hydrophobe|Water repellency]] treatments\n* [[Gas laser|Gas discharge laser]] development\n* [[Plant hormone|Plant growth regulators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.devilsathletics.com Official athletics website]\n\n{{Colleges and Universities in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Colleges and universities in metropolitan Philadelphia}}\n{{Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference navbox}}\n\n{{coord|39.9461|-75.2075|region:US-PA_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sciences In Philadelphia}}\n[[Category:University of the Sciences| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1821]]\n[[Category:1821 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University City, Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = University of the Sciences\n| motto        = ''Nosse haec omnia salus est''\n| mottoeng = ''To know all this is health''\n| established  = 1821\n| type         = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment    = Approx. $170 million\n| president    = Paul Katz, MD\n| undergrad    = 2,246\n| postgrad     = 418\n| city         = [[Philadelphia]]\n| state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = [[Urbanization|Urban]]\n| free_label   = Athletics\n| free         = 12 varsity teams, 17 intramural clubs\n| mascot       = Devils, \"Drake the Devil\"\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.usciences.edu}}\n| footnotes    = \n| image_name   = University of the Sciences logo.png\n| faculty      = 190\n| colors       = Maroon and slate {{color box|#460017}}&nbsp;{{color box|#B7B7B7}}\n| affiliations = [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[NCAA]], [[Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference|CACC]], [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Sciences''' ('''USciences'''), officially the '''University of the Sciences in Philadelphia''', is a private university in [[Philadelphia]], [[United States]]. USciences offers bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees in [[pharmacy]] and other health-related disciplines. USciences was established in 1821 as the '''Philadelphia College of Pharmacy''', to become the first pharmacy college in the nation.\n\n==History==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2011}}\n{{advert|section|date=December 2011}}\n}}\n[[File:University of the Sciences.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Campus entrance]]\nThe history of the University of the Sciences began when 68 Philadelphia apothecaries met in [[Carpenters' Hall]] in 1821 to establish improved scientific standards and to train more competent apprentices and students. They sought to enhance their vocation, as well as protect public welfare. Nearly a year later, they organized and incorporated the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy (PCP), the first college of pharmacy in the nation. The school is sometimes colloquially called a \u201cfake school\u201d due to its lack of recognition in the collegiate world.\n\nToday, the university has 30 degree-granting programs in three colleges. Its more than 2,300 students have enrolled in premier programs in the health sciences, ranging across pharmacy with its direct entry doctoral program to pre-med to physical therapy to healthcare business and health policy. Students study almost the entire range of the health sciences in one of its three colleges:\n\n* Philadelphia College of Pharmacy \u2014 North America's first school of pharmacy and the start of the University, graduates the pharmacists and scientists who deliver and discover the healthcare innovations that advance patient care.\n* Samson College of Health Sciences \u2014 educates the vital healthcare professionals who add immeasurably to the quality of life at each step\u2014from prevention to diagnosis to recovery of the patient care continuum.\n* Misher College of Arts and Sciences \u2014 provides a specialized undergraduate foundation for the sciences, with research and discovery at its core, for students seeking advanced degrees to lead in the basic and applied health sciences and serve humanity.\n\nAfter its conception in 1821, the college began to grow in enrollment, curriculum, and stature. Although matriculation was originally limited to men, the college became coeducational in 1876, and issued the first pharmacy degree to a woman in the United States, Dr. [[Susan Hayhurst]], in 1883.<ref name=Contributions>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B3dZEmPUoBcC&lpg=PA10&pg=PA10 |title=American Women Pharmacists: Contributions to the Profession |last1=Henderson |first1=Metta Lou |last2=Worthen |first2=Dennis B. |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=9780789010926 |page=10 |date=8 March 2002 |accessdate=29 November 2016 |via=Google Books}}</ref> The college initially emphasized the biological and chemical sciences as mainstays of the curriculum in pharmacy but later instituted separate curricula in three other areas: bacteriology, biology and chemistry.\n\nIn 1921, the name of the institution was changed to Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science, with state authorization to grant not only the baccalaureate degree, but also the master's and doctorate in all four disciplines.\n\nAs the world of science continuously made advancements throughout the decades, the college evolved and expanded its curriculum to prepare students for the new wave of scientific breakthroughs. The college also enhanced the role of the humanities and social sciences in its science-based curricula. Primarily a commuter campus in its early days, the institution began to transform into one in which residential life and extracurricular activities played a larger role in student development.\n\nThe Commonwealth of Pennsylvania approved the institution's application for university status in February 1997. In recognition of the broad spectrum of new health and science programs introduced by the institution, the college changed its name to reflect the broader range of academic opportunities offered to its students. On July 1, 1998, Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science officially unveiled its new identity as University of the Sciences in Philadelphia.\n\nA brand update in 2010 refocused the University's messaging and logos. The overall name was simplified for marketing purposes to University of the Sciences in order to emphasize a national and global reach, while a new logo transitioned the USP acronym to USciences to address awareness issues. In addition, the tag line \u201cWhere science and healthcare converge\u201d was adopted to define both what the University is and what it is not.\n\nIn September 2017, the University launched a tuition reset for all students who enroll beginning in fall 2018. Undergraduate students will not pay more than $25,000 per year in tuition and general fee* for undergraduate coursework. And for those students who are accepted into one of the University's accelerated, 6-year doctoral programs in pharmacy, physical therapy, or occupational therapy, the University lowered and simplified the tuition and general fee*. The lower tuition is fixed for the student's academic career. *This pricing does NOT include room and board, health insurance, or any professional, clinical, or transportation fees.<ref>[http://www.usciences.edu/lowertuition \"The tuition equation just got easier\"], University of the Sciences website</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the University announced that Mayes College of Healthcare Business and Policy would be dissolved as of July 1, 2018. With that, the Department of Pharmaceutical and Healthcare Business would become a part of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usciences.edu/news/2018/usciences-announces-college-restructuring-for-2018-19.html|title=USciences Announces College Restructuring for 2018-19|website=University of the Sciences}}</ref>\n\n===Shaping the profession of pharmacy===\n[[William Procter, Jr.]], often described as \"the father of American pharmacy\", was a PCP professor from 1846\u20131874, as well as serving as an officer of the board. He and [[Daniel B. Smith]] were instrumental in the founding of the American Pharmaceutical Association, the national professional society of pharmacists, which was founded and organized in Philadelphia in 1852. It is now called the American Pharmacists Association (APhA), the first established and largest professional association of pharmacists in the United States. The more than 50,000 members of APhA include practicing pharmacists, pharmaceutical scientists, pharmacy students, pharmacy technicians and others interested in advancing the profession.\n\nIn 1868, John Maisch, PCP professor (1866\u20131893) and dean (1879\u20131893), proposed the creation of a pharmaceutical board to be appointed by the governor of each state and established the term \"registered pharmacist\". He shared his proposal with each governor and, by 1878, nine states had adopted pharmacy laws which licensed pharmacists. Every state now, of course, has a Board of Pharmacy which regulates the practice of pharmacy.\n\nStarted in 1820, the [[United States Pharmacopeia]] laid down the standards for manufacturing drugs. For more than a hundred years, PCP faculty members were instrumental in its development, serving as editors throughout many editions.\n\nIn 1825, the first periodical in the United States devoted to the art and science of pharmacy, the ''American Journal of Pharmacy'', was published by PCP.\n\nPCP professors Franklin Bache and [[George Bacon Wood|George B. Wood]] compiled a comprehensive commentary on drugs, ''The Dispensatory of the United States of America''. First published in 1833, the ''Dispensatory'' was authored and edited for more than a hundred years by successive generations of faculty at the college.\n\nIn 1885, PCP professor [[Joseph P. Remington]] published ''The Practice of Pharmacy'', which soon became established as the standard text in the field. Later renamed ''Remington: The Science and Practice of Pharmacy'', this comprehensive reference work remains widely used throughout the world. The 22nd edition was published in September 2012 jointly by [[Pharmaceutical Press]] and the University of the Sciences.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usciences.edu/aboutUSP/USPhistory.shtml| title=USP History}}</ref>\n\n===Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy===\nThe Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usciences.edu/about/marvin-samson-center-for-the-history-of-pharmacy/index.html|title=Marvin Samson Center for the History of Pharmacy \u2013 University of the Sciences|work=usciences.edu|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> is an integral part of the University of the Sciences in Philadelphia.  The center's mission is to serve as an educational, cultural and research resource for the university, pharmacy professionals, historians and the general public through its collections of artifacts, objects and records representative of all aspects of pharmacy, including the pharmacy college's history. Through changing exhibitions, tours and programs, the center aims to deepen appreciation of the past, present and future significance of the pharmacy industry in the broader social context and in the development of American life, especially in the city of Philadelphia and the surrounding region.\n\n===Campus expansion program===\nThe university doubled the size of the campus in 1998 when it acquired an adjacent, vacant industrial site. (This site was formerly the home of the original Breyers Ice Cream factory which closed its Philadelphia operation in the early 1990s.) BLT Architects designed the Athletic and Recreation Center (ARC) in August 2003. BLT Architects channeled the ambience of a traditional college campus through this building. ARC is situated between a new campus quad and a commuter parking lot. Its design features a 1,000 seat event gymnasium, recreation gymnasium, natatorium, fitness areas and a 1/10 mile indoor track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blta.com/#/3/0/0/12/|title=Home \u2013 BLTa|work=BLTa|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> The McNeil Science and Technology Center (McNeil STC) was officially dedicated September 2006. Additional building projects are being planned.\n\nThe McNeil Science and Technology Center houses many new classrooms, computer research rooms and teaching laboratories as well as the undergraduate and graduate programs in biology, bioinformatics/computer science and math/physics/statistics. The centerpiece of the center is a 400-seat auditorium equipped with modern audio/visual equipment.\n\nIn fall 2014, the University opened its newest building, the Integrated Professional Education Complex (IPEX) and demonstrates USciences\u2019 commitment to preparing graduates for careers in the life sciences and health sciences professions. The 57,000-square-foot, three-story building showcases an integrated education model that permits students from several disciplines, including physician assistant studies, pharmacy, physical therapy, occupational therapy, exercise science, psychology and healthcare business and policy, to obtain traditional and hands-on experience. This integrated education model gives students an opportunity to fully understand its value in their everyday practice. IPEX combines innovative learning spaces and student lounge space with simulation labs, a clinical lab, mock patient exam rooms and conference rooms. It will also serve as a hub for students to study, interact and learn with and from one another. IPEX houses the provisionally accredited physician assistant studies graduate professional program. A green-roof system that emphasizes the University's commitment to the environment and sustainability, measures 20,000 square feet and will absorb nearly 15,000 gallons of water when fully saturated. IPEX earned three Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.\n\n==Academics==\nUniversity of the Sciences in Philadelphia has over 30 degree-granting programs for students from which to choose. The University is composed of three colleges: the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, Samson College of Health Sciences''',''' and Misher College of Arts & Sciences.\n\n=== Exchange agreements ===\nThe university has an exchange agreement with the [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)]] that allows ten students from each university to take one course a semester at the other. The university also has an agreement with the [[New York University]] Study Abroad Program that will allow University of the Sciences students to study at NYU campuses in Asia, Africa and Europe for a semester or a year.\n\n===The J. W. England Library===\nThe Library of the University of the Sciences in Philadelphia was formed in 1821 at the second meeting of the Board of Trustees. Since its beginnings, the library has been considered one of the premier collections of pharmaceutical science in the country. In 1973, the library moved into its present quarters, the free-standing Joseph W. England Library. Small but specialized, the collection is particularly strong in pharmacy, pharmacognosy, pharmaceutics and foreign drug compendia. Other areas of specialization include toxicology, pharmacology and physical therapy. Contained in the Leopold Helfand Rare Book and Archives Room is a collection of seventeenth and eighteenth century botanicals, including a book once owned by Isaac Newton. Since the university and its graduates were fundamental to the building of the United States pharmaceutical industry, the university archives are of interest to anyone researching the origins of the pharmaceutical industry.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2016}}\n[[File:USciDevils.png|thumb|Official athletics logo.]]\nThe University of the Sciences (USciences) teams participate as a member of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'s [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]. The Devils are a member of the [[Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference]] (CACC). Men's sports include baseball, basketball, cross country, golf, tennis and track & field; while women's sports include basketball, cross country, softball, tennis, track & field and volleyball. The baseball team participates in the [[Bill Giles Invitational]] tournament for Division II teams in the Philadelphia area.\n\n==Alumni==\nUniversity of the Sciences has launched the careers of many innovative and pioneering individuals in the field of health care, including the founders of six of the world's leading pharmaceutical companies:\n* Dr. [[Susan Hayhurst]]  (Class of 1883) \u2013 longtime head of the pharmaceutical department at the [[Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia]] and the first woman to receive a pharmacy degree in the United States<ref name=Contributions/>\n\n=== Major pharmaceuticals ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2011}}\n* Sir [[Henry Wellcome]] (Class of 1874) \u2013 co-founder of Burroughs Wellcome and Company, which is now part of [[GlaxoSmithKline]].\n* [[Silas Mainville Burroughs (pharmacist)|Silas M. Burroughs]] (Class of 1877) \u2013 co-founder of Burroughs Wellcome and Company, which is now part of [[GlaxoSmithKline]].\n* [[Josiah K. Lilly Sr.]] (Class of 1882) \u2013 father of Eli Lilly ('07). President of [[Eli Lilly and Company]]. The company was founded by Josiah's father, [[Colonel Eli Lilly]].\n* [[Eli Lilly (industrialist)|Eli Lilly]] (Class of 1907) \u2013 president of Eli Lilly and Company. The company was founded by Eli's grandfather, [[Colonel Eli Lilly]].\n* [[Robert L. McNeil, Jr.]] (Class of 1938) \u2013 chairman and CEO of [[McNeil Laboratories]] Inc., now part of [[Johnson & Johnson]]. Campus building named after him.\n\n===Alumni contributions===\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2018}}\nUniversity of the Sciences alumni have also contributed to the [[invention]] of well-known products, \n* [[Hires Root Beer]] extract\n* [[Photocopier|Photocopy toner]] and electrographic [[ink]]s\n* [[Polyurethane]]s\n* [[Silicone]]-based adhesives\n* [[Hydrophobe|Water repellency]] treatments\n* [[Gas laser|Gas discharge laser]] development\n* [[Plant hormone|Plant growth regulators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.devilsathletics.com Official athletics website]\n\n{{Colleges and Universities in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Colleges and universities in metropolitan Philadelphia}}\n{{Central Atlantic Collegiate Conference navbox}}\n\n{{coord|39.9461|-75.2075|region:US-PA_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sciences In Philadelphia}}\n[[Category:University of the Sciences| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1821]]\n[[Category:1821 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University City, Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "Usciences", "label": "safe", "comment": "2020 updates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "Pagal Adilabadi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name        = Ahmed Shareef \n| image       = \n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = Pagal Adilabadi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|5|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Nizamabad district|Nizamabad]], [[Telangana]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = {{circa}}{{death year and age|2007|1941}}\n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Poet]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| period      = \n| genre       = \n| subject     = [[Humour]], [[Love]]\n| movement    = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n}}\n'''Ahmed Shareef''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0631\u064a\u0641 '''}}), (19 May 1941 \u2013 {{circa}}2007), popularly known as  '''Pagal Adilabadi''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0631\u064a\u0641 \u067e\u0627\u06af\u0644 \u0639\u0627\u062f\u0644 \u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f\u0649'''}}), was an [[Urdu poet]] from [[Adilabad]], India. He wrote ''mazahiya shayari'' or humorous poetry in his native dialect of [[Hyderabadi Urdu]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Funny weekend in store for poetry lovers|author= |url= http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/09/stories/2005120919240200.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> His [[pen name]], \"Pagal\", means \"crazy\" in Urdu.<ref>{{cite news |title= An endeavour that has restored the pride|author= |url= http://www.hindu.com/2007/09/08/stories/2007090858410300.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPagal Adilabadi was born 19 May 1941 in [[Nizamabad district]], [[Telangana]]. He was a teacher in a government school in [[Adilabad]], [[Telangana]], hence the name.\n\n==Career==\nPagal Adilabadi wrote humorous poems, ''shayari'' in [[Urdu language|Urdu]].\n\nThe book ''Khusur Phusr'' collects his life work. In the initial stage of his life he never published his works. He was busy working as a teacher, but after retiring from his job, he started writing the books.\n\nAhmed Sherif died at the age of 66<ref name=\"Statesman\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/dear-postmaster-1502550969.html |title=Dear postmaster |date=24 December 2017 |website=The Statesman |language=en-US |access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> while working on his book ''Bagare Baingan''.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Khusur Phusr'' - Goonj publications (Nizamabad).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crGgK5T4Rxk Video clip of Pagal poetry recital]\n* [http://www.urdulife.com/mushaira/poet.cgi?ap_ahmed_sharif_pagal Audio clips of Pagal Adilabadi on UrduLife.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060115192031/http://mushaira.org/ppage.php?poet_name=Paagal+Adilabadi Audio clips of Pagal Adilabadi on Mushaira.org]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adilabadi, Pagal}}\n[[Category:Urdu poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Nizamabad]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name        = Ahmed Shareef \n| image       = \n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = Pagal Adilabadi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|5|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Nizamabad district|Nizamabad]], [[Telangana]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = {{circa}}{{death year and age|2007|1941}}\n| death_place = \n| occupation  = [[Poet]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| period      = \n| genre       = \n| subject     = [[Humour]], [[Love]]\n| movement    = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n}}\n'''Ahmed Shareef''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0631\u064a\u0641 '''}}), (19 May 1941 \u2013 {{circa}}2007), popularly known as  '''Pagal Adilabadi''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0631\u064a\u0641 \u067e\u0627\u06af\u0644 \u0639\u0627\u062f\u0644 \u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f\u0649'''}}), was an [[Urdu poet]] from [[Adilabad]], India. He wrote ''mazahiya shayari'' or humorous poetry in his native dialect of [[Hyderabadi Urdu]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Funny weekend in store for poetry lovers|author= |url= http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/09/stories/2005120919240200.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> His [[pen name]], \"Pagal\", means \"crazy\" in Urdu.<ref>{{cite news |title= An endeavour that has restored the pride|author= |url= http://www.hindu.com/2007/09/08/stories/2007090858410300.htm|newspaper= The Hindu|date= |accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPagal Adilabadi was born 19 May 1941 in [[Nizamabad district]], [[Telangana]]. He was a teacher in a government school in [[Adilabad]], [[Telangana]], hence the name.\n\n==Career==\nPagal Adilabadi wrote humorous poems, ''shayari'' in [[Urdu language|Urdu]].\n\nThe book ''Khusur Phusr'' collects his life work. In the initial stage of his life he never published his works. He was busy working as a teacher, but after retiring from his job, he started writing the books.\n\nAhmed Sherif died at the age of 66<ref name=\"Statesman\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/dear-postmaster-1502550969.html |title=Dear postmaster |date=24 December 2017 |website=The Statesman |language=en-US |access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> while working on his book ''Bagare Baingan''.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Khusur Phusr'' - Goonj publications (Nizamabad).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crGgK5T4Rxk Video clip of Pagal poetry recital]\n* [http://www.urdulife.com/mushaira/poet.cgi?ap_ahmed_sharif_pagal Audio clips of Pagal Adilabadi on UrduLife.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060115192031/http://mushaira.org/ppage.php?poet_name=Paagal+Adilabadi Audio clips of Pagal Adilabadi on Mushaira.org]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adilabadi, Pagal}}\n[[Category:Urdu poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Nizamabad]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pagal_Adilabadi"}
{"title_page": "Santiago Villalba Mederos", "text_new": "{{short description|American fugitive}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox FBI Ten Most Wanted\n| name               = Santiago Villalba Mederos\n| image              = Santiago Mederos.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                =\n| caption            = Photograph taken in 2009\n| charge             = *[[Murder]] (2 counts)\n*[[Unlawful Flight to Avoid Prosecution]]\n| reward             = $100,000\n| alias              = \"Pucho\"<br>\"Stretch\"<br>Santiago Mederes<br>Santiago Mederos<br>Santiago V. Mederos<br>Santiago Medeors<br>Santiago Villalva Mederos\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|6|5}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tacoma, Washington]], [[United States]]\n| cause              = \n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| race               = Hispanic\n| gender             = Male\n| height             = 5 ft 10 in\n| weight             = 140 lb\n| occupation         =\n| parents            = \n| siblings           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| conviction         = \n| conviction_penalty = \n| conviction_status  = \n| added_date         = September 25, 2017\n| caught_date        = \n| remove_date        = \n| surrendered_date   = \n| number             = 515\n| status             = Currently on the FBI's top ten most wanted list\n}}\n'''Santiago \"Pucho\" Villalba Mederos''' (born June 5, 1991)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/interpols-most-wanted-americans/48/|title=Interpol's most wanted Americans|date=2018-05-31|access-date=August 31, 2018|language=en}}</ref> is an American [[fugitive]] who was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on September 25, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/new-top-ten-fugitive-santiago-villalba-mederos|title=New Top Ten Fugitive|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=August 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/fbi-10-most-wanted-criminals-list-2017-11|title=These are the fugitives on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list \u2014 and how they got there|work=Business Insider|access-date=September 3, 2018}}</ref> He is wanted for two murders in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/santiago-mederos|title=SANTIAGO VILLALBA MEDEROS|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=August 31, 2018}}</ref> Mederos was the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2010s|515th fugitive to be placed]] on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list. The FBI offers a reward of up to $100,000 for information leading to his capture.\n\n==Background==\nMederos was born on June 5, 1991 and is an alleged murderer and gang member from the state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. He was just an 18-year-old teenager when he allegedly killed and wounded multiple people on different occasions in Washington in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/santiago-villalba-mederos-accused-in-2-slayings-added-to-fbis-most-wanted-list/|title=Santiago Villalba Mederos, accused in 2 slayings, added to FBI's \"Most Wanted\" list|access-date=August 31, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He is a member of the Eastside Lokotes Sure\u00f1os (ELS) gang, a violent gang based in Washington. Mederos is described as Hispanic, 5 feet 10 and 140 pounds, with black hair and brown eyes. He has a tattoo of the letter \u201cS\u201d on his left shoulder and a tattoo of the letter \u201cE\u201d on his right shoulder. He speaks fluent English and Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article175323776.html|title=Tacoma man added to FBI's 10 Most Wanted|date=September 25, 2017|publisher=The News Tribune|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Murders==\nOn February 7, 2010, Mederos and six other gang members from the ELS were out driving a stolen van through [[Tacoma, Washington]] in search for rival gang members. They were after the gang in retaliation for a shooting that had occurred two days earlier in which an ELS member was badly wounded. They came across 20-year-old Camille Love and her brother 19-year-old Josh Love. Camille was driving while Josh was sat in the passenger seat of the vehicle. They had just left a family dinner and were driving to a friend's house. The siblings were stopped at a traffic light and were inside a red car. Josh was wearing a red coat, and red was the color associated with the rival gang. Mistaking Josh for a rival gang member, Mederos and at least one other gang member opened fire into the vehicle. They fatally shot Camille and seriously wounded Josh. Josh was shot twice and was hit in the arm and on his side. Neither Josh or Camille were associated with any gang.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lookout in Camille Love shooting sees 50-plus years shaved off his original sentence|date=October 11, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article219889750.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2010, Mederos and another gang member ransacked a car in an apparent robbery in a South Tacoma alley. They suspected the owner of the car owed the gang money. The duo then got into a fight with three other men who confronted them. Mederos shot at the group of people as he fled on foot and fatally shot 25-year-old Saul Lucas-Alfonso. Lucas-Alfonso again was not associated with any gang.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/crime/tacoma-fugitive-accused-of-2-murders-added-to-fbis-ten-most-wanted-list/|title=Tacoma fugitive accused of 2 murders added to FBI's Ten Most Wanted list|date=September 26, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe leader of the Eastside Lokotes Sure\u00f1os, Juan Zuniga-Gonzalez, was blamed for the murders. The death of Love led to a crackdown from the [[Tacoma Police Department]] against the ELS. Unhappy with Zuniga's leadership and the unwanted attention from Love's murder, four members of the gang who were in prison at the time ordered the murder of Zuniga-Gonzalez.<ref>{{cite news|title=4 inmates charged with conspiring to kill gang leader|date=December 14, 2010|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/4-inmates-charged-with-conspiring-to-kill-gang-leader/|newspaper=The Seattle Times|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> On May 12, 2010, Zuniga-Gonzalez was murdered at his home in Tacoma. 15-year-old Naitaalii Toleafoa and 17-year-old Juan Ortiz drove to Zuniga's home. Ortiz fatally shot Zuniga in the back of the head in his garage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teen charged in 2010 murder of Tacoma gang leader|date=December 6, 2013|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/teen-charged-in-2010-murder-of-tacoma-gang-leader|publisher=Komo News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Both suspects then fled to [[Mexico]] after the assassination. Toleafoa was captured in 2012 and Ortiz was arrested in [[Mexico City]] in August 2016. Both were extradited from Mexico to stand trial for the murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man who hid in Mexico on trial for 2010 Tacoma homicide|date=April 5, 2017|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/man-who-hid-in-mexico-on-trial-for-2010-tacoma-homicide/509563318|publisher=KIRO-TV|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nSeven ELS gang members were charged in Love's murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plea of not guilty to murder charge|date=December 14, 2010|url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article25273336.html|publisher=The Olympian|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Five of the seven have been captured and are serving prison sentences ranging from 12 to 75 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=He got 75 years in the fatal shooting of Tacoma's Camille Love. Now he'll get a new trial|date=January 18, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article195484724.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Mederos and fellow ELS gang member Richard Charles Sanchez are still on the run. According to the FBI, Mederos is believed to have fled to Mexico after the murders. Authorities also believe he may have returned to the U.S. since. Mederos has family in the Las Grutas, [[Guerrero]] and [[Cuernavaca]] areas of Mexico. Mederos is charged with first-degree murder, attempted first-degree murder, first-degree conspiracy to commit murder and unlawful possession of a firearm.\n\nJesus Mederos, the older brother of Santiago Mederos, was arrested in May 2017 in Cuernavaca, Mexico. Jesus was responsible for the fatal shooting of 18-year-old Robert Tapia at a Tacoma intersection in October 2006. After the murder he fled to Mexico and spent 12 years on the run before being captured.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 12 years on the run, man arrested in 2006 fatal shooting in Tacoma|date=August 10, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article216439740.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The FBI hopes the arrest of Santiago's brother will help in finding him.<ref>{{cite news|title=FBI hopes brother's arrest in Mexico, return to Tacoma leads to capture of 'Ten Most Wanted' fugitive|date=August 10, 2018|url=https://q13fox.com/2018/08/10/fbi-hopes-brothers-arrest-in-mexico-return-to-tacoma-leads-to-capture-of-ten-most-wanted-fugitive/|publisher=Q13 Fox|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> A reward of $100,000 has been offered by the FBI for information that leads to the arrest and extradition of Mederos.<ref name=\"theyucatantimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theyucatantimes.com/2017/05/reward-offered-in-search-for-fugitive-who-may-be-in-mexico/|title=Reward offered in search for fugitive who may be in Mexico|date=May 19, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives by year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mederos, Santiago Villalba}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2010 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:Crime in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on murder charges]]\n[[Category:Gang members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American fugitive}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox FBI Ten Most Wanted\n| name               = Santiago Villalba Mederos\n| image              = Santiago Mederos.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                =\n| caption            = Photograph taken in 2009\n| charge             = *[[Murder]] (2 counts)\n*[[Unlawful Flight to Avoid Prosecution]]\n| reward             = $100,000\n| alias              = \"Pucho\"<br>\"Stretch\"<br>Santiago Mederes<br>Santiago Mederos<br>Santiago V. Mederos<br>Santiago Medeors<br>Santiago Villalva Mederos\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|6|5}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tacoma, Washington]], [[United States]]\n| cause              = \n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| race               = Hispanic\n| gender             = Male\n| height             = 5 ft 10 in\n| weight             = 140 lb\n| occupation         =\n| parents            = \n| siblings           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| conviction         = \n| conviction_penalty = \n| conviction_status  = \n| added_date         = September 25, 2017\n| caught_date        = \n| remove_date        = \n| surrendered_date   = \n| number             = 515\n| status             = Currently on the FBI's top ten most wanted list\n}}\n'''Santiago \"Pucho\" Villalba Mederos''' (born June 5, 1991)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/interpols-most-wanted-americans/48/|title=Interpol's most wanted Americans|date=2018-05-31|access-date=August 31, 2018|language=en}}</ref> is an American [[fugitive]] who was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on September 25, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/new-top-ten-fugitive-santiago-villalba-mederos|title=New Top Ten Fugitive|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=August 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/fbi-10-most-wanted-criminals-list-2017-11|title=These are the fugitives on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list \u2014 and how they got there|work=Business Insider|access-date=September 3, 2018}}</ref> He is wanted for two murders in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/santiago-mederos|title=SANTIAGO VILLALBA MEDEROS|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=August 31, 2018}}</ref> Mederos was the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2010s|515th fugitive to be placed]] on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list. The FBI offers a reward of up to $100,000 for information leading to his capture.\n\n==Background==\nMederos was born on June 5, 1991 and is an alleged murderer and gang member from the state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. He was just an 18-year-old teenager when he allegedly killed and wounded multiple people on different occasions in Washington in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/santiago-villalba-mederos-accused-in-2-slayings-added-to-fbis-most-wanted-list/|title=Santiago Villalba Mederos, accused in 2 slayings, added to FBI's \"Most Wanted\" list|access-date=August 31, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He is a member of the Eastside Lokotes Sure\u00f1os (ELS) gang, a violent gang based in Washington. Mederos is described as Hispanic, 5 feet 10 and 140 pounds, with black hair and brown eyes. He has a tattoo of the letter \u201cS\u201d on his left shoulder and a tattoo of the letter \u201cE\u201d on his right shoulder. He speaks fluent English and Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article175323776.html|title=Tacoma man added to FBI's 10 Most Wanted|date=September 25, 2017|publisher=The News Tribune|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Murders==\nOn February 7, 2010, Mederos and six other gang members from the ELS were out driving a stolen van through [[Tacoma, Washington]] in search for rival gang members. They were after the gang in retaliation for a shooting that had occurred two days earlier in which an ELS member was badly wounded. They came across 20-year-old Camille Love and her brother 19-year-old Josh Love. Camille was driving while Josh was sat in the passenger seat of the vehicle. They had just left a family dinner and were driving to a friend\u2019s house. The siblings were stopped at a traffic light and were inside a red car. Josh was wearing a red coat, and red was the color associated with the rival gang. Mistaking Josh for a rival gang member, Mederos and at least one other gang member opened fire into the vehicle. They fatally shot Camille and seriously wounded Josh. Josh was shot twice and was hit in the arm and on his side. Neither Josh or Camille were associated with any gang.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lookout in Camille Love shooting sees 50-plus years shaved off his original sentence|date=October 11, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article219889750.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2010, Mederos and another gang member ransacked a car in an apparent robbery in a South Tacoma alley. They suspected the owner of the car owed the gang money. The duo then got into a fight with three other men who confronted them. Mederos shot at the group of people as he fled on foot and fatally shot 25-year-old Saul Lucas-Alfonso. Lucas-Alfonso again was not associated with any gang.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/crime/tacoma-fugitive-accused-of-2-murders-added-to-fbis-ten-most-wanted-list/|title=Tacoma fugitive accused of 2 murders added to FBI's Ten Most Wanted list|date=September 26, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe leader of the Eastside Lokotes Sure\u00f1os, Juan Zuniga-Gonzalez, was blamed for the murders. The death of Love led to a crackdown from the [[Tacoma Police Department]] against the ELS. Unhappy with Zuniga's leadership and the unwanted attention from Love's murder, four members of the gang who were in prison at the time ordered the murder of Zuniga-Gonzalez.<ref>{{cite news|title=4 inmates charged with conspiring to kill gang leader|date=December 14, 2010|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/4-inmates-charged-with-conspiring-to-kill-gang-leader/|newspaper=The Seattle Times|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> On May 12, 2010, Zuniga-Gonzalez was murdered at his home in Tacoma. 15-year-old Naitaalii Toleafoa and 17-year-old Juan Ortiz drove to Zuniga's home. Ortiz fatally shot Zuniga in the back of the head in his garage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teen charged in 2010 murder of Tacoma gang leader|date=December 6, 2013|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/teen-charged-in-2010-murder-of-tacoma-gang-leader|publisher=Komo News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Both suspects then fled to [[Mexico]] after the assassination. Toleafoa was captured in 2012 and Ortiz was arrested in [[Mexico City]] in August 2016. Both were extradited from Mexico to stand trial for the murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man who hid in Mexico on trial for 2010 Tacoma homicide|date=April 5, 2017|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/man-who-hid-in-mexico-on-trial-for-2010-tacoma-homicide/509563318|publisher=KIRO-TV|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nSeven ELS gang members were charged in Love\u2019s murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plea of not guilty to murder charge|date=December 14, 2010|url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article25273336.html|publisher=The Olympian|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Five of the seven have been captured and are serving prison sentences ranging from 12 to 75 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=He got 75 years in the fatal shooting of Tacoma's Camille Love. Now he'll get a new trial|date=January 18, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article195484724.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Mederos and fellow ELS gang member Richard Charles Sanchez are still on the run. According to the FBI, Mederos is believed to have fled to Mexico after the murders. Authorities also believe he may have returned to the U.S. since. Mederos has family in the Las Grutas, [[Guerrero]] and [[Cuernavaca]] areas of Mexico. Mederos is charged with first-degree murder, attempted first-degree murder, first-degree conspiracy to commit murder and unlawful possession of a firearm.\n\nJesus Mederos, the older brother of Santiago Mederos, was arrested in May 2017 in Cuernavaca, Mexico. Jesus was responsible for the fatal shooting of 18-year-old Robert Tapia at a Tacoma intersection in October 2006. After the murder he fled to Mexico and spent 12 years on the run before being captured.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 12 years on the run, man arrested in 2006 fatal shooting in Tacoma|date=August 10, 2018|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article216439740.html|publisher=The News Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The FBI hopes the arrest of Santiago's brother will help in finding him.<ref>{{cite news|title=FBI hopes brother's arrest in Mexico, return to Tacoma leads to capture of 'Ten Most Wanted' fugitive|date=August 10, 2018|url=https://q13fox.com/2018/08/10/fbi-hopes-brothers-arrest-in-mexico-return-to-tacoma-leads-to-capture-of-ten-most-wanted-fugitive/|publisher=Q13 Fox|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> A reward of $100,000 has been offered by the FBI for information that leads to the arrest and extradition of Mederos.<ref name=\"theyucatantimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theyucatantimes.com/2017/05/reward-offered-in-search-for-fugitive-who-may-be-in-mexico/|title=Reward offered in search for fugitive who may be in Mexico|date=May 19, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives by year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mederos, Santiago Villalba}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2010 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:Crime in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on murder charges]]\n[[Category:Gang members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_Villalba_Mederos"}
